(1, 2, 'Expanding & Factorising', 'Expanding & Factorising are two of the most used methods in algebra. Quadratic equations can be written in \r\neither expanded or factorised form. To expand a quadratic equation, you use the FOIL method, which stands for Firsts, Outers, Inners, Lasts. First multiply the first numbers in each bracket. Second, multiply the first number in the first bracket by the second number in the second bracket. Third, multiply the second number in the first bracket by the first number in the second bracket. Fourth, multiply the second numbers in each bracket. Fifth, simplify your answer. Finally, multiply each part of the equation by the number outside the bracket.\r\n\r\nTo factorise a quadratic equation, first look for a common factor in the co-efficient of each part and put this in front of the two brackets. Next multiply, the co-efficient of a by c. Find two numbers that add to equal b and multiply to equal c and separate them as b values. Then factorise the common factor out of the first two parts of the equation and then the last two parts of the equation. Then you have found the two numbers in each bracket.\r\n'),
(2, 2, 'Algebraic Fractions', 'In level 1, you will learn how to simplify fractions with algebraic terms in them. Whenever there is a quadratic on at least one side of the fraction, the key to simplifying is factorising. If you factorise correctly, you should see that one bracket is exactly the same on both sides of the fraction. If so, you can get rid of both of the brackets and finish your simplification.\r\n\r\nYou may also be given two fractions to simplify into one. The key to simplifying these to make the denominator of each fraction equal. To do this, multiply any factor that is not on the particular fraction\'s denominator to the numerator. Then you can blend the two fractions together. To finish simplifying the fraction, expand all the brackets on the numerator and then if possible, factorise the parts into two brackets. If any brackets, match any on the denominator, you can cancel those brackets out completely.'),
(3, 2, 'Solving Linear Equations', 'In level 1, you will probably be asked to solve linear equations. These are one of the easiest solving questions in algebra. Many of these questions come in application-style, such as perimeters of 2D shapes. The easiest way to solve linear equations is to put like terms of the variable on one side of the equation and parts that are just numbers on the other side of the equation. Then multiply or divide both sides, so that the side of the equation with the variable in it has a co-efficient of 1. Finally, simplify both sides of the equation and solve for the unknown variable.'),
(4, 2, 'Solving Quadratic Equations', 'In algebra, solving quadratic equations is very common. The key to solving a quadratic equation is to first make one side of the equation equal to zero, if it is not already equal to zero. Then, factorise the equation. You will be left with two brackets each with the variable in them. This means that either bracket must be equal to zero. Your last step is to set each bracket equal to zero and solve for the variable. You should have two solutions. In level 1, all solutions will be real numbers. Sometimes, in the context of an application question, one of the solutions may not be correct in the context of the question. For example, lengths cannot be negative and some objects must be whole numbers.'),
