(10, 10, 'Integration', 'While one half of calculus is differentiation, the other half is about integration, which is the opposite of\r\ndifferentiation. With integration, you begin with the gradient function. When a gradient function is\r\nintegrated, the shape of the graph represented by the function changes but in the opposite way to\r\ndifferentiation. For example, when we integrate a quadratic gradient function, we get the function,\r\nwhich is a cubic.\r\n\r\nThis is how we integrate functions:\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nTo integrate a function, divide the co-efficient of each part by one greater than the power of x and\r\nincrease the power of each part by one. Add an x at the end of parts that were just a number originally\r\nand add a c at the end of the new equation. This will be any real number. If you are given a co-ordinate\r\nthat the function passes through, you can substitute the x and y co-ordinates in to find the value of c.\r\n\r\nThis is the equation of the function:\r\n'),
